        <section data-role="page" id="week2Discussion">
            <section data-role="header">
                <section class="center-wrapper"><img src="img/AVF1310_03.png" alt="titleImage" width="100" height="35"></section>
            </section>
            <section data-role="content">
                <ul data-role="listview" data-inset="true" id="week2" class="week">
                    <li><h1>Here is my Week 2 Discussion Post</h1></li>
                    <li>
                    <p>
                    1. Twitter can be used for logins and payments in a few different ways.  Instead of having someone <br>create an entirely new username and password for your app, you can allow them to login with <br>their Twitter info.  This can allow you to easily be able to post info about what your doing in <br>the app to Twitter.  One of those things that you could be doing in your app is purchasing <br>items or services.  Because you are already logged into Twitter, your user can easily share <br>info about those purchases to Twitter.  This increases exposure and shows that people are using <br>your app.  I know, personally, that if I see one of my friends using an app, I am more inclined <br>to try it out.<br>
                    <br>
                    2. We need JSON-P specifically for this class because we are trying to get information from a different <br>domain.  We have to be able to use the results that we get from a different domain in a way <br>that fits best for our app.  Normally, when you make a JSON request to a different domain, the <br>data that you get back is often not in a format that you can do something with it.  With JSON-<br>P, you are allowed to add a special parameter to your domain call that allows the data that you <br>get back to be in a format that you can use more effectively.<br>
                    <br>
                    3. Some of the more popular websites allow JSONP requests.  Not every major website allows for JSONP <br>requests, but sites like Instagram, Flickr, foursquare, bit.ly, Vimeo, and Dropbox do.  Native <br>features like the camera and geolocation would pair perfectly with Instagram and Flickr.  The <br>Media and Contacts features would pair nicely with Dropbox or Vimeo because you could share your <br>media with Dropbox, or share Vimeo results with your contacts.  foursquare really only works <br>with geolocation because that is what the foursquare service is all about.  Storage is also one <br>that would work well with Dropbox.  You could allow your user to save either to local storage <br>or to a service like Dropbox.<br>
                    <br>
                    4. I think this month I want to keep it simple and focus mainly on the camera and geolocation features.  <br>I want to be able to upload pictures to either Flickr or Instagram, and also allow for the <br>geolocation of each photo to be obtained.  I think also trying to implement foursquare <br>functionality would also be fun to explore.  If those do not pan out, I would like to try to get <br>media from Vimeo and allow those results to be filtered.<br>
                    <br>
                    5. The biggest “lesson learned” from past classes is that I would focus too much on design first, <br>rather than functionality.  I would spend too much time on how things looked or the layout of <br>information, and then run out of time for what the project or assignment was actually about.  I <br>have tried to change my approach now to get basic design done first, then add all <br>functionality, then finally, fine-tune and clean up the design.<br>
                    </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </section>
