        <section data-role="page" id="week3Discussion">
            <section data-role="header">
                <section class="center-wrapper"><img src="img/AVF1310_03.png" alt="titleImage" width="100" height="35"></section>
            </section>
            <section data-role="content">
                <ul data-role="listview" data-inset="true" id="week3" class="week">
                    <li><h1>Here is my Week 3 Discussion Post</h1></li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                       1. The very first thing I need to do is add ALT tags to my images.  I am terrible at remembering to <br>add those into my images and I did not even think about how they could be related to <br>accessibility.  I also need to increase the contrast of the elements in my Demo App.  I <br>would imagine that someone with some visual disabilities would have a hard time <br>distinguishing the buttons and links in my app.
                        <br>
                        <br>
                       2. It looks like that majority of frustrations that arise from both screen readers and mobile screen <br>readers tend to be about inaccessible Flash Content.  Flash content gets skipped over by a <br>lot of the readers and that can be very confusing for the user.  Other frustrations are <br>CAPTCHA verifications are not accessible, links and buttons do not make sense, image <br>descriptions do not make sense, and complex forms are not understood.  A lot of these <br>problems and frustrations stem from the designer of the website not thinking about people <br>with accessibility needs when designing.  I know that it was not something I thought about <br>when making my Demo app.  Having proper HTML markup and proper ALT tags help solve some of <br>these issues.  Other ones can be embedding your videos into HTML and using the most up-to-<br>date CAPTCHA’s that have accessibility support.
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        3. There are numerous devices available for people to use that have accessibility needs.  There are <br>braille keyboards available for people with vision disabilities.  These keyboards are <br>exactly like a normal keyboard, except the keys have braille on them.  Another device is <br>desktop video magnifier.  While these devices can be very expensive, they are a great <br>addition to anyone with low-vision.  They basically show a magnified image of whatever is <br>placed on the device.  This make for reading books or magazines much easier.
                        <br>
                        <br>
                       4. Two apps that greatly aide in accessibility are Dragon Dictate and Fleksy.  Dragon Dictate is a <br>text reader and speech dictation software.  It will not only read what is on the screen, it <br>also allows you to take notes and write messages just by speaking  Fleksy is a very easy to <br>use messenger.  It simplifies and enlarges the keyboard to make it very easier to see.  It <br>also put a different background on the text to make it easier to see the contrast.  Now while <br>these apps are great, iOS 7 has some amazing accessibility features built right into it.  <br>These include voice dictation with Siri, larger text options, assistive touch, motion <br>reduction, bolder text, and inverted colors.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </section>
